\par GGF9, first JSDL meeting, Tuesday 10/07/03, 4pm to 5:30pm.
\par Meeting minutes.
\par 
\par 
\par Purpose of the meeting: some dissemination of information.
\par -go thru basic structure of JSDL, spec document.
\par -present outline to make writing the spec easier.
\par -Attributes categories. Is it the right way to 
\par  present JSDL attributes?
\par 
\par 
\par Brief motivation for JSDL.
\par --------------------------
\par architecture agnostic job description language etc.
\par 
\par allow "job mgt" and interoperability between "entities" such as 
\par job submission client, queuing services, execution resources, etc. 
\par 
\par Structure
\par ----------
\par a) "core set" of attributes
\par --> JSDL supplies semantics and syntax of attributes
\par 
\par b) extension mechanism
\par not clear yet. to add proprietary attributes.
\par maybe <any>....
\par 
\par Charter
\par -------
\par a) set of MUST attributes
\par b) '    ' MAY   ' ' '  (file transfer, dependencies)
\par 
\par NO CONCERN about scheduling and selection of resources 
\par but of course JSDL should enable it.
\par 
\par 
\par We accept proposal for terms. If conflicts we will hash them out 
\par in conf calls.
\par 
\par deliverables: 
\par -------------
\par a) binding-independent spec: attributes, semantics, 
\par             interrelationships, value ranges
\par 
\par b) normative XML schema
\par 
\par c) document of translation tables
\par     --> using knowledge of specialists from 
\par         different systems
\par    Darren: One of the reasons: interoperability. 
\par          Too costly to drop brand new thing into 
\par          an existing system.
\par    Ali: EPCC set up new system. Scheduler went 
\par         from LSF to Load Leveler. 
\par    Alain: who will write those adapters? 
\par         Ali:    best if the ISVs do it. 
\par    Andreas: thought about writing already translators 
\par          to other languages? DRMAA? If DRMAA-JSDL 
\par          translator would save some work...
\par         Ali: proof-of-concept student project based 
\par              on DRMAA set and IBM LoadLeveler. He has 
\par              job submission client to translate 
\par              from DRMAA client invocation to actual 
\par              LoadLeveler.
\par 
\par         Comment: if own schema, can do XSLT to do 
\par               translation when not too sophisticated.
\par 
\par Question: is it really critical to restrict to batch jobs?
\par Ali: start with batch job languages/systems. Set up the basis. 
\par Other things are out of scope right now. 
\par Steve: keep as much as possible notion of covering other types of jobs. 
\par 
\par Even if don't put in language at this stage can keep in back 
\par of our minds.
\par 
\par 
\par update and logistics
\par --------------------
\par since GGF8: new proposal - chartered mid-August.
\par Telecons. We have so far: 
\par - basic spec document outline
\par - proposal for job terms made to group
\par 
\par JSDL Logistics
\par --------------
\par migration of Web site to GridForge.
\par 
\par weekly telecon meetings:
\par - time will rotate every 4 weeks for fairness.
\par - Next set of 4 meetings start on Oct 15.
\par - start time 13:00 GMT until Oct 26
\par              14:00 GMT after Oct 26
\par - meeting time posted to list before every meeting
\par - if times are unpractical, send comments to the list
\par 
\par JSDL Attribute Categories
\par -------------------------
\par Coarse-grained break-up of attributes.
\par [slide gives examples of what types of attributes 
\par go under each category]
\par Invitation for comments.
\par Karl: semantic benefit to those categories?
\par Ali: reasons: 
\par      1)  help facilitate writing of spec. Make manageable pieces 
\par      of work.
\par      Take the first category, tackle it for a few weeks, 
\par      define its attributes, and move on to the next category.
\par      2) maybe job description with application that only deals with 
\par         certain set of attributes.
\par         Example: accounting app. If JSDL structure reflects 
\par         could help.
\par          Comment(Alain): limited mapping since not all 
\par              domain-specific groupings will be covered
\par 
\par Ali: A document is linked to unique instance of a job. That is not 
\par to say you cannot reuse the document to submit another job instance.
\par 
\par Ali: JSDL not dictating anything about how job description is written. 
\par Steve: only what we're defining is structure of job document.
\par 
\par Question: use case for environment variables?
\par should be in resource category?
\par 
\par Karl: we should not worry too much about the categories.
\par 
\par Darren: let's define all attributes THEN only group them. Maybe 
\par we will throw away some categories or merge them, we'll see at 
\par that point.
\par 
\par Systems to Consult with
\par -----------------------
\par Would be nice to gather informational documents about 
\par each language.
\par 
\par Which direction to go to define attributes? 
\par compare systems or start from scratch? 
\par Steve: probably both directions at the same time.
\par 
\par Ming: probably useful to capture command-line features 
\par not just attributes in description language.
\par 
\par Karl: concern about assumptions about operational context 
\par and architecture, not stated explicitly. When are we defining 
\par service interfaces?
\par Darren: want to approach from other end. How I am going to 
\par use JSDL?
\par Karl: exactly what is missing. We need to define how to use 
\par this "job document".
\par Darren: start from use case. 
\par 
\par Question: users should not see all attributes..
\par 
\par Domain application should shield users from attributes 
\par that are not needed.
\par 
\par Thought about other formats? MOF? UML? 
\par Jenny: Charter says XML so it will be XML.
\par 
\par Question:: how can application provider specifies its requirements
\par using JSDL? 
\par Suggestion: use WS-Agreement for a standard way to specify 
\par those requirements.
\par 
\par Comment from Andrea on job ID: better to be job "name" 
\par because cannot be decided by the client.
\par Chris: whoever you talk to will give you a handle. 
\par No guarantee of uniqueness.
\par --> let's discuss specific attributes on the list or 
\par conference call.
